<Author>Honi
<Content>Superficial style without substance... ....more Ikea than Phillipe Starke. I鈥檓 sorry to report that we were very disappointed with our stay at the B-Hotel this past weekend. Starting with the good points of the hotel, it is reasonably well located, just a 15 minute taxi ride (without traffic) from Barcelona airport (as opposed to Girona airport, where Ryanair flies into) and within walking distance of the train station. It is also within walking distance of Barcelona鈥檚 main attractions if you don鈥檛 mind long walks, which I enjoy. It was also moderately priced at around 鈧?75 per night for the room, excluding breakfast.The negatives are that the hotel is located on Gran Via, one of Barcelona鈥檚 main thoroughfares and, at night, a drag strip for wanna-be Spanish Grand Prix drivers. All night long, drivers blared their car horns in sync in support of the Spanish Grand Prix driver, Fernando Alonso, who had just won the race. We hardly slept a wink. Even the night before the Grand Prix we couldn鈥檛 sleep for all the traffic roaring just outside all night long 鈥?it was like sleeping on a motorway overpass.We also didn鈥檛 find the staff very helpful. I was quite thirsty after walking around warm Barcelona all day and quickly polished off the 3 tiny bottles of water in the room鈥檚 mini-bar. However, when we asked the front desk if they could provide us with some replacement bottles of water, they said no! The hotel bar, such that it is, was already long closed at midnight, and they declined our practical suggestion of opening up one of the unoccupied rooms to give us bottles of water from an unused mini-bar. I had to make do with half a glass of warm water left over on my bedside table from the previous night (which fortunately the maid had neglected to take away when she cleaned the room), and my partner had to quaff a bottle of too-sweet tonic water.What possible excuse can there be not to be able to give guests some additional bottles of water, even if the request is made at midnight? Another disappointment was the character-less hotel bar. I had expected to enjoy a gin and tonic in the evening at the poolside bar on the roof, but in fact, there was no poolside bar anymore. Even the bar in the main lobby was non-existent after 9 p.m. and completely lacking in atmosphere.Breakfast at 鈧?5 for two was a modest continental-style buffet with a range of cereals, bread rolls, croissants, hams and cheese, which quickly ran out and weren鈥檛 replaced. Hard boiled eggs were provided, but cooked breakfasts aren鈥檛 offered. Coffee and hot water for tea are dispensed from push-top Thermos-type containers rather than freshly made to order. Although the hotel has a certain minimalist style that makes it more appealing than, say, a Holiday Inn, it has absolutely none of the buzzy atmosphere or style of the hotels it is apparently trying to emulate, such as The Mercer in NYC, or The Sanderson, One Aldwych and St Martins Lane in London. I have stayed in each of those hotels, and B-Hotel is nothing more than a cheap, Ikea-styled facsimile of those truly stylish hotels. The metallic bedspread had pulls and loose threads on it and the carpets in the hallways were stained.All in all, I would say if you're a light sleeper or looking for a truly stylish hotel, you should stay elsewhere. If you just want a change from the usual BB and chain hotel experience and don't mind an absense of real style and atmosphere, soundproofing or bottles of water at midnight, then by all means stay at B-Hotel. 
